                            <h1>
                            Maintaining Spirituality
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p2" class="">President Marion G. Romney</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p" class="">Second Counselor in the First Presidency</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">03115_000_007</span>
			<div class="figure">
				<img src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/gospel-library/magazine/ensignlp.nfo:o:1db4.jpg" alt="President Marion G. Romney">
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p3" class="">My beloved brothers and sisters, I seek the Spirit of the Lord as I give you a message. I have chosen to speak about maintaining spirituality. This subject came to mind as I pondered the admonition of Jacob, Nephi&rsquo;s brother:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p4" class="">&ldquo;Remember, to be carnally-minded is death, and to be spiritually-minded is life eternal&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/9.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 9:39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p5" class="">President McKay defined spirituality as &ldquo;the consciousness of victory over self, and of communion with the infinite. Spirituality,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;impels one to conquer difficulties and acquire more and more strength. To feel one&rsquo;s faculties unfolding and truth expanding the soul is one of life&rsquo;s sublimest experiences&rdquo; (David O. McKay, <span class="emphasis">Stepping Stones to an Abundant Life,</span> comp. Llewelyn R. McKay, Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1971, p. 99).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p6" class="">Through the Prophet <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a>, the Lord revealed the truth that &ldquo;all spirit is matter, but it is more fine or pure, and can only be discerned by purer eyes&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/131.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 131:7</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p7" class="">Abraham said: &ldquo;The Lord had shown unto me &hellip; the intelligences that were organized before the world was; &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p8" class="">&ldquo;And God saw these souls that they were good, &hellip; for he stood among those that were spirits&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/abr/3.22-23?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Abr. 3:22&ndash;23</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p9" class="">These spirits were the offspring of God, who, according to John, is also a spirit. He&mdash;that is, John&mdash;wrote:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p10" class="">&ldquo;God is a Spirit: and they that worship him must worship him in spirit&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/4.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 4:24</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p11" class="">Although God&rsquo;s spirit is clothed in &ldquo;a body of flesh and bones as tangible as man&rsquo;s&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/130.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 130:22</a>), his body is neither temporal nor carnal, for, says he, &ldquo;all things unto me are spiritual&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/29.34?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 29:34</a>). &ldquo;I &hellip; created [all things] by the word of my power, which is the power of my Spirit.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p12" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; both spiritual and temporal&mdash;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p13" class="">&ldquo;First spiritual, secondly temporal, which is the beginning of my work; and again, first temporal, and secondly spiritual, which is the last of my work&mdash;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p14" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; all things unto me are spiritual, and not at any time have I given unto you a law which was temporal&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/29.30-32,34?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 29:30&ndash;32, 34</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p15" class="">Being in tune with God is being spiritual. Man himself is naturally spiritual. His spirit is a child of God. The spirits of &ldquo;the inhabitants [of all worlds] are begotten sons and daughters unto God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/76.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 76:24</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p16" class="">Furthermore, &ldquo;the Spirit [of the Lord] giveth light to every man that cometh into the world; and the Spirit enlighteneth every man through the world, that hearkeneth to the voice of the Spirit.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p17" class="">&ldquo;And every one that hearkeneth to the voice of the Spirit cometh unto God, even the Father&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/84.46-47?lang=eng#45" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 84:46&ndash;47</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p18" class="">&ldquo;Every spirit of man was innocent in the beginning; and God having redeemed man from the fall, men became again, in their infant state, innocent before God.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p19" class="">&ldquo;And that wicked one cometh and taketh away light and truth&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/93.38-39?lang=eng#37" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 93:38&ndash;39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p20" class="">This loss of spirituality began with the children of Adam and Eve when they refused to obey the teachings of their parents.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p21" class="">You will recall that Adam was taught the gospel by an angel (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.6-8?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:6&ndash;8</a>), and that thereafter &ldquo;he was caught away by the Spirit of the Lord,&rdquo; and was baptized and received the Holy Ghost. &ldquo;And thus he was born of the Spirit&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/6.64-65?lang=eng#63" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 6:64&ndash;65</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:10</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p22" class="">&ldquo;And Adam and Eve blessed the name of God, and they made all things known unto their sons and their daughters.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p23" class="">&ldquo;And Satan came among them [those sons and daughters], saying: I am also a son of God; and he commanded them, saying: Believe it not [that is, the teachings of their parents]; and they believed it not, and they loved Satan more than God. And men began from that time forth to be carnal, sensual, and devilish&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.12-13?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:12&ndash;13</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p24" class="">Spirituality comes by faith, repentance, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/baptism?lang=eng">baptism</a>, and reception of the Holy Ghost. One who has the companionship of the Holy Ghost is in harmony with God. He is, therefore, spiritual. Spirituality is sustained by so living as to keep that companionship.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p25" class="">A sure way for us to do this is to learn what our duties are and perform them. They include obeying the first and second great commandments: &ldquo;Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind&rdquo; and &ldquo;Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/22.37,39?lang=eng#36" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 22:37, 39</a>). They also include obedience to the Ten Commandments and the Sermon on the Mount, implementing the Articles of Faith, and prayer.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p26" class="">As to the importance of prayer in maintaining spirituality, it is interesting to note that the first recorded commandment Adam and Eve received from the Lord, following their expulsion from the garden, was &ldquo;that they should worship the Lord their God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:5</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p27" class="">The next heavenly being who spoke to Adam was the angel who told him that the sacrifice he was offering was &ldquo;a similitude of the sacrifice of the Only Begotten of the Father. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p28" class="">&ldquo;Wherefore,&rdquo; he added, &ldquo;thou shalt do all that thou doest in the name of the Son, and thou shalt repent and call upon God in the name of the Son forevermore&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.7-8?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:7&ndash;8</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p29" class="">From then until now, no divine commandment has been more frequently repeated than the commandment to pray in the name of the Lord <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p30" class="">One of the most impressive lessons on the importance of prayer was received by the brother of Jared when &ldquo;the Lord &hellip; stood in a cloud and talked with him. And for the space of three hours did the Lord talk with the brother of Jared, and chastened him because he remembered not to call upon the name of the Lord.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p31" class="">&ldquo;And,&rdquo; continues the record, &ldquo;the brother of Jared repented of the evil which he had done, and did call upon the name of the Lord for his brethren who were with him. And the Lord said unto him: I will forgive thee and thy brethren of their sins; but thou shalt not sin any more, for ye shall remember that my Spirit will not always strive with man&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/2.14-15?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 2:14&ndash;15</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p32" class="">It was not very long thereafter that the brother of Jared prayed with such faith that the Lord Jesus <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>, then a premortal spirit, appeared to him, and said: &ldquo;Behold, I am Jesus Christ. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p33" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; this body, which ye now behold, is the body of my spirit; &hellip; and even as I appear unto thee to be in the spirit will I appear unto my people in the flesh&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/3.14,16?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 3:14, 16</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p34" class="">Another convincing evidence of the power of prayer in helping one to maintain spirituality is the account given by Enos, Jacob&rsquo;s son, who wrote:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p35" class="">&ldquo;I will tell you of the wrestle which I had before God, before I received a remission of my sins.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p36" class="">&ldquo;Behold, I went to hunt beasts in the forests; and the words which I had often heard my father speak concerning eternal life, and the joy of the saints, sunk deep into my heart.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p37" class="">&ldquo;And my soul hungered; and I kneeled down before my Maker, and I cried unto him in mighty prayer and supplication for mine own soul; and all the day long did I cry unto him; yea, and when the night came I did still raise my voice high that it reached the heavens.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p38" class="">&ldquo;And there came a voice unto me, saying: Enos, thy sins are forgiven thee, and thou shalt be blessed.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p39" class="">&ldquo;And I, Enos, knew that God could not lie; wherefore, my guilt was swept away.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p40" class="">&ldquo;And I said: Lord, how is it done?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p41" class="">&ldquo;And he said unto me: Because of thy faith in Christ, whom thou hast never before heard nor seen. And many years pass away before he shall manifest himself in the flesh; wherefore, go to, thy faith hath made thee whole.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p42" class="">&ldquo;Now, it came to pass that when I had heard these words I began to feel a desire for the welfare of my brethren, the Nephites; wherefore, I did pour out my whole soul unto God for them.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p43" class="">&ldquo;And while I was thus struggling in the spirit, behold, the voice of the Lord came into my mind again, saying: I will visit thy brethren according to their diligence in keeping my commandments&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/enos/1.2-10?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Enos 1:2&ndash;10</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p44" class="">Searching the scriptures is another powerful assist in maintaining spirituality. Alma bears witness to this in his account of the miraculous missionary accomplishments of the sons of Mosiah.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p45" class="">&ldquo;They had waxed strong in the knowledge of the truth,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;for they were men of a sound understanding and they had searched the scriptures diligently, that they might know the word of God.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p46" class="">&ldquo;But this is not all; they had given themselves to much prayer, and fasting; therefore they had the spirit of prophecy, and the spirit of revelation, and when they taught, they taught with power and authority of God&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/17.2-3?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 17:2&ndash;3</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p47" class="">Prayer and searching the scriptures are companion aids in both obtaining and maintaining spirituality.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p48" class="">&ldquo;Pray always,&rdquo; said the Lord to the Prophet Joseph, &ldquo;that you may come off conqueror; yea, that you my conquer Satan, and that you may escape the hands of the servants of Satan that do uphold his work&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/10.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 10:5</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p49" class="">Concerning the scriptures, John reports that Jesus said, &ldquo;Search the scriptures; for in them ye think ye have eternal life: and they are they which testify of me&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/5.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 5:39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p50" class="">The purpose of the sacrament is to promote the maintenance of spirituality. Both the revealed prayers over the bread and over the water contain the phrase, &ldquo;that they [who partake] may &hellip; have his Spirit to be with them&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/20.77,79?lang=eng#76" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 20:77, 79</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p51" class="">In a revelation recorded in section 59 of the Doctrine and Covenants, given through the Prophet Joseph Smith 7 August 1831 for the guidance of the Saints who had recently arrived in Jackson County, Missouri, the Lord revealed a list of instructions essential to their maintaining spirituality. In part he said:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p52" class="">&ldquo;Behold, blessed, saith the Lord, are they who have come up unto this land with an eye single to my glory. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p53" class="">&ldquo;For those that live shall inherit the earth, and those that die shall rest from all their labors, and their works shall follow them; and they shall receive a crown in the mansions of my Father, which I have prepared for them.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p54" class="">&ldquo;Yea, blessed are they whose feet stand upon the land of Zion, who have obeyed my gospel; for they shall receive for their reward the good things of the earth, and it shall bring forth in its strength.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p55" class="">&ldquo;And they shall also be crowned with blessings from above, yea, and with commandments not a few, and with revelations in their time&mdash;they that are faithful and diligent before me.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p56" class="">&ldquo;Wherefore, I give unto them a commandment, saying thus: Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, with all thy might, mind, and strength; and in the name of Jesus Christ thou shalt serve him.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p57" class="">&ldquo;Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself. Thou shalt not steal; neither commit adultery, nor kill, nor do anything like unto it.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p58" class="">&ldquo;Thou shalt thank the Lord thy God in all things.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p59" class="">&ldquo;Thou shalt offer a sacrifice unto the Lord thy God in righteousness, even that of a broken heart and a contrite spirit.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p60" class="">&ldquo;And that thou mayest more fully keep thyself unspotted from the world, thou shalt go to the house of prayer and offer up thy sacraments upon my holy day;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p61" class="">&ldquo;For verily this is a day appointed unto you to rest from your labors, and to pay thy devotions unto the Most High;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p62" class="">&ldquo;Nevertheless thy vows shall be offered up in righteousness on all days and at all times;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p63" class="">&ldquo;But remember that on this, the Lord&rsquo;s day, thou shalt offer thine oblations and thy sacraments unto the Most High, confessing thy sins unto thy brethren, and before the Lord.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p64" class="">&ldquo;And on this day thou shalt do none other thing, only let thy food be prepared with singleness of heart that thy fasting may be perfect, or, in other words, that thy joy may be full.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p65" class="">&ldquo;Verily, this is fasting and prayer, or in other words, rejoicing and prayer.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p66" class="">&ldquo;And inasmuch as ye do these things with thanksgiving, with cheerful hearts and countenances, not with much laughter, for this is sin, but with a glad heart and a cheerful countenance&mdash;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p67" class="">&ldquo;Verily I say, that inasmuch as ye do this, the fulness of the earth is yours, the beasts of the field and the fowls of the air, and that which climbeth upon the trees and walketh upon the earth;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p68" class="">&ldquo;Yea, and the herb, and the good things which come of the earth, whether for food or for raiment, or for houses, or for barns, or for orchards, or for gardens, or for vineyards;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p69" class="">&ldquo;Yea, all things which come of the earth, in the season thereof, are made for the benefit and the use of man, both to please the eye and to gladden the heart;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p70" class="">&ldquo;Yea, for food and for raiment, for taste and for smell, to strengthen the body and to enliven the soul.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p71" class="">&ldquo;And it pleaseth God that he hath given all these things unto man; for unto this end were they made to be used, with judgment, not to excess, neither by extortion.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p72" class="">&ldquo;And in nothing doth man offend God, or against none is his wrath kindled, save those who confess not his hand in all things, and obey not his commandments.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p73" class="">&ldquo;Behold, this is according to the law and the prophets; wherefore, &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p74" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; learn that he who doeth the works of righteousness shall receive his reward, even peace in this world, and eternal life in the world to come.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p75" class="">&ldquo;I, the Lord, have spoken it, and the Spirit beareth record&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/59.1-24?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 59:1&ndash;24</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p76" class="">Spirituality, brothers and sisters, will come to all who will follow this pattern, for the Lord himself has said: &ldquo;It shall come to pass that every soul who forsaketh his sins and cometh unto me, and calleth on my name, and obeyeth my voice, and keepeth my commandments, shall see my face and know that I am;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p77" class="">&ldquo;And that I am the true light that lighteth every man that cometh into the world;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p78" class="">&ldquo;And that I am in the Father, and the Father in me, and the Father and I are one&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/93.1-3?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 93:1&ndash;3</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1979/11/maintaining-spirituality.p79" class="">Such is the pattern, my beloved brothers and sisters, for maintaining spirituality. May we all succeed in attaining it and pleasing the Lord and find him, I humbly pray in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
